tweet: Read more about all of the challenges schools face as they reopen: http://bbc.in/CV19UKSchoolCosts …

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Schools in England will get access to £1bn of funding - which must be spent on "catch-up" activities

Schools will get £80 for each primary and secondary pupil

However, the scheme has been criticised for not targeting students who most need the money

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKSchoolCosts … pic.twitter.com/5B5z6RaQVc

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
From September, in England, schools are expected to pay for any additional cleaning or staff costs from their existing budgets

In Wales & Scotland, at least £20m has been put aside in each country to help cover cleaning costs

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKSchoolCosts … pic.twitter.com/2cklCHPL8G

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
In England, the government offered grants of up to £75,000 depending on the size of the school, for March - July

This was mainly aimed at helping schools stay open over Easter and extra support for the government's free school meals scheme

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKSchoolCosts … pic.twitter.com/OQiRuIASNV

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The National Foundation for Educational Research estimates Covid costs this academic year could be significant:

- Primary schools could spend up to £280,000 (20% of an average budget)
- Secondary schools could spend £720,000 (12% of an average budget)

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKSchoolCosts … pic.twitter.com/ujo0K5afa3

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Almost all of the 1,821 schools who answered the survey had purchased additional cleaning supplies, while around 85% had purchased signage, tape or barriers

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKSchoolCosts … pic.twitter.com/YN2apajpaA

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
A survey by the National Association of Head Teachers found many schools had already incurred costs in the period to September: 

- 2/3 had additional staff costs for cleaning
- 1/2 were purchasing / renting hand-washing stations

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKSchoolCosts … pic.twitter.com/4YvXwPfuKt

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Most schools across the UK are fully reopening, for the first time since March

To keep pupils and staff safe they are having to make their buildings Covid-secure and are providing catch-up help for students

But can they afford Covid-19 costs?

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
How will travel to/from school work? 

🚲 Walking or cycling is encouraged
🚌 School transport groups are being asked to move children in bubbles, provide hand sanitiser, social distance where possible and children 11+ will be asked to wear face coverings

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSchools … pic.twitter.com/7nTxMri1rX

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
What will happen if there’s an outbreak in a school?

A mobile testing unit may be sent to test the infected student’s class, their year group, and the whole school if needed 🧪

Closing a school will ''not generally be necessary'' the UK government says

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSchools … pic.twitter.com/lg9sz8Q8bf

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
What counts as a coronavirus outbreak in a school?

📈 Two or more confirmed cases within 14 days
📈 A rise in the number of children off with suspected Covid-19

If this happens, schools must work with local health protection teams

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSchools … pic.twitter.com/ZwUsMSqQX4

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
How will a school day work?

⏰ Staggered start and finish times 
👭 Classes in “protective bubbles” to minimise contact
👬 Assemblies or collective worship with one group only
🏉 No contact sport or unnecessary sharing of objects

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSchools … pic.twitter.com/PjkmXE9gNs

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Do students have to wear face coverings?

The rules differ, depending on where you are in the UK

PM Boris Johnson has said masks don't work well in classrooms: "you can't teach with face coverings and you can't expect people to learn with face coverings”

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSchools … pic.twitter.com/Ml1dpmD2KI

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
What rules must schools in England follow?

🧼 Frequent hand washing
🤧 Promoting good hygiene
🧹 Enhanced cleaning procedures 
📏 Social distancing
❌ No pupils with Covid-19 symptoms, or any from a household with symptoms, can attend http://bbc.in/CV19UKSchools

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Do children in England have to go to school?

The government say children must attend unless they, or a close contact, develop symptoms or test positive for coronavirus

Head teachers can follow up on absences and issue sanctions including possible fines http://bbc.in/CV19SchoolFines

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
There are concerns about big job losses when the scheme ends, but the chancellor has repeatedly ruled out extending it

A £1,000 bonus for every furloughed employee, kept on until end of January 2021, will be paid by government, aimed at protecting jobs 

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusFurlough … pic.twitter.com/Ki2Jz5YCb5

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Some have criticised the decision to close the scheme at the end of October, but it has been backed by the Bank of England

The institution says workers should be helped to ''move forward'' and not be kept in unproductive jobs

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusFurlough … pic.twitter.com/9GCi6V5G9A

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Since 1 August, employers have had to pay National Insurance and pension contributions for their staff

Now, businesses will have to pay 10% of furloughed staff wages too

At the start of October, this will rise to 20% of their wages

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusFurlough … pic.twitter.com/FIu9OUQfsi

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Since July, furloughed employees have been able to go back to work part-time

An employer could, for example, pay someone to work two days a week, while the furlough scheme would cover the other three days not worked

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusFurlough … pic.twitter.com/WSZDJMwguO

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Under the Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme, furloughed workers have been able to receive 80% of their pay, up to a maximum of £2,500 a month

Employers made £34.7bn furlough claims by 9 August, with the government set to pay an estimated £80bn in total

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusFurlough … pic.twitter.com/5ySob7b6YS

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
From today, businesses with staff on furlough will have to pay 10% of their wages

tweet: Read more about the challenges faced by doctors fighting coronavirus and flu, as we head into winter: http://bbc.in/CV19FluWinter

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
“With Covid-19 still likely to be circulating during flu season, it is more important than ever to have the flu vaccination”

A Department for Health spokeswoman says the government “urge anyone who is eligible to take up the offer of vaccination”

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKFlu  pic.twitter.com/UkpWLfpp19

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
“People think the flu is not that bad, that is even for people who are in the risk groups”

Dr Tonia Thomas says it is important people at risk get the jab: “It is only when they contract an infection that they realise their body responds differently”

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKFlu  pic.twitter.com/v5uCcenPhf

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The NHS says it wants to ensure the highest-risk patients are at the front of the queue when the immunisation programme starts, in September

Health bosses hope people aged 50-64 will be offered the jab later this year, if there are enough supplies

 http://bbc.in/CV19FluWinter  pic.twitter.com/yG5tVzkaFV

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
In England, the vaccine will be offered free to a variety of groups

Officials in Scotland, Northern Ireland and Wales are planning to expand their vaccination programmes to cover a similar section of the population

 http://bbc.in/CV19FluWinter  pic.twitter.com/UPydBo3Gyf

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
“There is almost a complacency around the vaccine”

Prof Heidi Larson says “some years it really isn’t that effective against all strains. But I would certainly urge people to take it anyway as you wouldn’t want the strains that it does protect against” http://bbc.in/CV19UKFlu

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
While this is encouraging, the World Health Organization points out there needs to be a degree of caution when interpreting the trends

 http://bbc.in/CV19FluWinter  pic.twitter.com/8nfFaIY74G

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Countries in the southern hemisphere, including South Africa, have also reported lower levels of flu than expected at this time of year

Scientists say this could partly be because lockdown measures and extra hand-washing reduce the spread of flu too

 http://bbc.in/CV19FluWinter  pic.twitter.com/56139ghNm6

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
A big flu season combined with coronavirus could overwhelm hospitals, experts say

But social distancing, masks and other hygiene measures in place to stop coronavirus should, in theory, decrease the amount of flu going around

 http://bbc.in/CV19FluWinter  pic.twitter.com/0QkCnBqd29

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
There is some evidence a double infection with coronavirus & flu is more deadly than either alone

But others think being infected with one virus could potentially help stop another from making you ill at the same time

This hasn’t been proven in this case
 http://bbc.in/CV19FluWinter  pic.twitter.com/s2vsGQn9gi

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The average number of estimated deaths in England for the past five annual flu seasons is more than 11,000

This ranges from almost 4,000 deaths in the flu ‘season’ in 2018-19 to more than 22,000 in 2017-18

 http://bbc.in/CV19FluWinter  pic.twitter.com/Fblu0AwIGd

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The flu (influenza) is a very common highly infectious disease

It can be dangerous - particularly for older adults, very young children, and people with underlying health conditions

While many can fight off the flu, sometimes things are more complicated

 http://bbc.in/CV19FluWinter  pic.twitter.com/PYPBmAkd4h

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Health bosses say they’ll offer 30 million people in the UK the flu vaccine, this year

The aim is to prepare for a winter with the annual flu season and a potential coronavirus surge

But how will it work? 

Will things be worse this year?

[Thread] http://bbc.in/CV19FluWinter

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Citizens Advice warn the most vulnerable are often at greatest risk of being contacted by fraudsters

 http://bbc.in/CV19Scams  pic.twitter.com/qH5Z35I4AV

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Local councils say they've seen a 40% increase in reported scams since the start of lockdown

Citizens Advice suggests one in three people in the UK have been targeted by a Covid-19 related scam

 http://bbc.in/CV19Scams  pic.twitter.com/2kJaizUYkF

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Some scammers are setting up fake social media profiles to manipulate victims into handing over money

Fake investment opportunities are being advertised on social media, encouraging victims to "take advantage of the financial downturn”

 http://bbc.in/CV19Scams  pic.twitter.com/1HcPEwEeDi

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
One scam involves a message stating the recipient has been fined £60 for leaving their home more than once a day

Links in these messages connect to websites that steal a victim's personal information or hack into their device

 http://bbc.in/CV19Scams  pic.twitter.com/8yBV81qe2o

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Local councils say people have also been contacted, fraudulently, by companies claiming to provide school meals 

Criminals have also been caught contacting care home residents offering to do shopping but instead stealing their cash

 http://bbc.in/CV19Scams  pic.twitter.com/MyWvjqlnrc

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Other lockdown-related scams include fake emails asking people to update TV subscriptions - aimed at helping fraudsters steal credit card information

 http://bbc.in/CV19Scams  pic.twitter.com/CljqqggTDX

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Some fraudsters host adverts for non-existent coronavirus-related products, taking cash and sending nothing

The Local Government Association has also warned about fake test kits, hand sanitisers and medical products claiming to treat or prevent Covid-19

 http://bbc.in/CV19Scams  pic.twitter.com/C4OYm0Jgmt

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Health-related scams are also circulating

One phishing scam claims the recipient has been in contact with someone diagnosed with Covid-19, then uses a fake website to steal personal or financial information

 http://bbc.in/CV19Scams  pic.twitter.com/WNUiYS2eXC

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Other official-looking emails are claiming to offer a "council tax reduction”, linking to a fake website to steal personal information

Another scam is offering help applying for universal credit, but fraudsters take some of the money for their "services"

 http://bbc.in/CV19Scams  pic.twitter.com/gs05I50TQ1

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Some scams pretend to help with financial support during the pandemic

Examples include fake government emails claiming to offer grants up to £7,500, and emails offering access to "Covid-19 relief funds", telling victims to hand over personal information

 http://bbc.in/CV19Scams  pic.twitter.com/NrH90F1T05

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Fraudsters are using coronavirus as an excuse to trick people out of their cash, banks warn

tweet: Read more about the research into the loss of smell and taste, with coronavirus: http://bbc.in/CV19SmellLoss

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The main symptoms of coronavirus are:
🌡️ High temperature
😷 New, continuous cough
👃 Loss of smell or taste

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSymptoms … pic.twitter.com/ZjbXGjQ1tB

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Experts suspect this is because the coronavirus affects the nerve cells directly involved with smell and taste sensation

These senses typically return within a few weeks in most people who recover from coronavirus

 http://bbc.in/CV19SmellLoss  pic.twitter.com/AC3SKfUQPv

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
It's not that their taste is weakened because their sense of smell is out of action, scientists say

Coronavirus patients with loss of taste really cannot tell the difference between bitter or sweet, research shows

 http://bbc.in/CV19SmellLoss  pic.twitter.com/mcLyh7MXTt

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
When Covid-19 patients have smell loss it tends to be sudden and severe

They usually don't have a blocked, stuffy or runny nose - most people with coronavirus can still breathe freely

 http://bbc.in/CV19SmellLoss  pic.twitter.com/Oc0qonz6mr

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet: Read more about your rights, and what your employer can and can’t do: http://bbc.in/CV19Redundancy

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
If you're facing redundancy, you may get paid time off to look for another job

If you have worked continuously for an employer for 2+ years you are allowed 40% of your working week off to attend interviews

Your employer should pay you for this time

 http://bbc.in/CV19Redundancy  pic.twitter.com/RIaahxBySf

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
If you still have holiday owed when you leave, you are entitled to be paid for that too

If a business has gone bust, then redundancy pay may be provided by the government

The first £30,000 of any redundancy pay is tax-free

 http://bbc.in/CV19Redundancy  pic.twitter.com/OBwl858YjM

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
If you have worked continuously for your employer for two years or more, you have the legal right to redundancy pay 

There is a statutory minimum but some employment contracts and employers are more generous

 http://bbc.in/CV19Redundancy  pic.twitter.com/VZPFumYUAF

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The amount of notice you are given will depend on how long you have been employed

You are entitled to a consultation with your employer if you are being made redundant

 http://bbc.in/CV19Redundancy  pic.twitter.com/gN2oRknkDV

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
You can be made redundant while on furlough, but the same rules of fairness must apply

Your employer also can’t discriminate and make you redundant, if, for example, you were over 70 and would need to take extra care with social distancing

 http://bbc.in/CV19Redundancy  pic.twitter.com/iMmi7ZCLp4

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Firms may ask for volunteers, and offer a redundancy payment

However, it is up to the employer whether they actually select those volunteers for redundancy

 http://bbc.in/CV19Redundancy  pic.twitter.com/pUbBlf1N3A

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
You must have been chosen fairly

Employers may make selections based on length of service (last in, first out) or disciplinary records

But they cannot discriminate

 http://bbc.in/CV19Redundancy  pic.twitter.com/CzvFghyqMk

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
When a business needs to reduce its workforce, it closes jobs and the people doing those jobs may be made redundant

It isn’t the same as getting sacked

If you’re made redundant, you have legal rights

 http://bbc.in/CV19Redundancy  pic.twitter.com/7vxnMTRsYd

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Job losses are becoming more common as businesses feel the financial effects of the coronavirus crisis

But what are your rights if you are made redundant?

[Thread] http://bbc.in/CV19Redundancy

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet: Read more about what a recession means for you, what action is being taken around the world, and how long experts think global economies will take to recover: http://bbc.in/Recession

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The Bank of England predicts the UK economy will grow in the third quarter of 2020, so technically, the recession could already be over

The IMF predicts that the world economy will grow next year, too

But no-one knows how strong the recovery will be

 http://bbc.in/Recession  pic.twitter.com/zA6TIc7sZF

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The pain of recession is typically not felt equally across society, and inequality can increase

School leavers may find it harder to get a first job, for example

Benefit recipients and public sector workers could also be disproportionately affected 

 http://bbc.in/Recession  pic.twitter.com/U5rs0w4AMb

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
A recession likely means job losses & fewer vacancies, especially in entry-level positions

Some may find it harder to get promotions or pay rises

The Bank of England says the UK's economic slump was less severe than expected but recovery will take longer
 http://bbc.in/Recession  pic.twitter.com/ps7WXrSBkO

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Recessions which carry on for a long time, or are particularly bad, are called depressions

The International Monetary Fund estimate the world’s economy will shrink by 4.9% this year, making it the worst recession since the Great Depression of the 1930s

 http://bbc.in/Recession  pic.twitter.com/av55DFElsm

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
When a country’s economy shrinks for two quarters in a row (six months) the change is classified as a recession

In the UK, in January to March UK GDP fell by 2.2%, while between April and June it fell by 20.4%

This is the largest contraction on record

 http://bbc.in/Recession  pic.twitter.com/ZP7vkWuzbY

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The UK economy has suffered its biggest fall on record

Between April and June, during lockdown, the economy shrank 20.4% compared with the first three months of the year

But, what is a recession and how could it affect you?

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet: Discover more tips on coping with the heat, and how to stay cool during the tropical weather http://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Remember, you will recover

We ideally need between six to hours hours of quality sleep to function at our best, but a few nights of interrupted sleep will do no long-lasting damage

 http://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/ayoxjC53gQ

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Think of the children

Children are normally quite sound sleepers once they nod off, but changes to routine can unsettle, so keep bed and bath times the same

Babies will sleep best when the temperature is kept between 16C and 20C
 http://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/GpC9SLTC0v

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Stay calm

Keep yourself busy - worrying about how much sleep you might get before heading to bed does little to relax you

And if you do struggle when in bed, read a book or listen to the radio, but avoid screen time as the blue light wakes your brain
 http://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/NLqVjFM0t0

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Stay hydrated

Drink plenty of water throughout the day, but avoid too much right before you head to bed, as a trip to the bathroom in the early hours won't help your attempt at catching a good night's sleep
 http://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/jfLjEWdhG4

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Chill your socks 

A fan is ideal (if you can lay your hands on one!) but alternatively, chilled socks can help keep your feet cool, lowering the temperature of your skin and body as a whole
 http://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/zfWjWRicWb

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Use thin sheets

Not only are they lighter, they will also absorb sweat
 http://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/qlML5xwndH

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Remember the basics

Shut any curtains in your room during the day to keep it as cool as possible

Open a window before bed to get a nice through breeze
 http://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/CQ4bsL26mH

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Keep to routines

Changing habits can disrupt sleep patterns, something that is not much help if you are struggling to get some kip
 http://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/WHleUlSKtj

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
No napping!

Hot weather can make us feel tired as our body fights to regulate our body temperature, but it is important to save that precious sleep for night time
 http://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/CnK7JE1oi6

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Temperatures reached 34C for the fifth day in a row today - thought to be an unprecedented event in the UK

That’s leading to warm nights too, with many struggling to sleep

So, here’s some tips from experts - to stop you counting sheep!
 http://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/TB7u4x19vU

 http://bbc.in/2PIbW9T  https://twitter.com/BBCBreaking/status/1293069307874770945 …

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
"The challenge for government is to ensure the peak isn't so much that it overburdens the healthcare system," says Prof Ball

Read more about the possibility of a second wave: 
 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSecondWave … pic.twitter.com/hle3rc3iCC

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
If we’re only just controlling the virus, even a small seasonal-boost could lead to the virus spreading

"A second wave is almost inevitable, particularly as we go towards the winter months,” says Prof Jonathan Ball from University of Nottingham

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSecondWave … pic.twitter.com/TSSN8ma9Ck

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Local flare ups will likely continue to happen in the next few weeks and months as restrictions are lifted

But they don't mean a guaranteed second wave

Winter may be a crucial time as other coronaviruses spread more readily then

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSecondWave … pic.twitter.com/CtRCLCDqKX

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
If there was a second wave, it’s likely to spread more slowly

But it could, theoretically, be bigger, as so many people are still susceptible to coronavirus

Experts say social distancing remains important in helping to stop the spread of the virus

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSecondWave … pic.twitter.com/R9m01TGccu

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The R number in the UK was at three at the start of the pandemic 

But, as our behaviour changes, scientists think it's unlikely the R value will get as high as that again

There is significant variation in R number estimates across the UK though

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSecondWave … pic.twitter.com/AGiQ8RduJ4

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Lifting lockdown restrictions too fast could trigger a second wave 

Lockdowns have caused massive disruption, but they have controlled the virus

Governments need to work out how to make things as normal as possible, while controlling the virus’ spread

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSecondWave … pic.twitter.com/QF7Qpzzpb7

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Will there be a second wave in the UK?

The potential is there - the virus is no less deadly or infectious than at the start of 2020

Only around 5% of people in the UK are thought to have been infected and there is no guarantee they’re all immune

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSecondWave … pic.twitter.com/2UhukHzGhw

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
For a second wave you need a sustained rise in infections 

Several European countries have reported a recent rise in cases

Other nations, which appeared to have controlled initial outbreaks, like Israel, Australia & Japan, have also seen cases rising

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSecondWave … pic.twitter.com/N8IogoaL4R

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
There is no formal definition of what counts as a second wave 

To say a wave has ended, the virus needs to be under control and there should be a substantial drop in cases

Some places, including some US states, are experiencing a bumpy first wave

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSecondWave … pic.twitter.com/oBrXgTbwTY

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The coronavirus pandemic is far from over

Some countries are still dealing with the original wave of infections

But even those who have managed to control the virus fear a possible “second wave”

Is it inevitable?

[Thread] http://bbc.in/CoronavirusSecondWave …

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The six things to remember not to do when wearing a face covering:

- Don't wear it on your chin
- Don't wear a loose-fitting mask
- Don't use it if it's damp / damaged
- Don't pull it away to speak
- Don't touch the front of it
- Don't share it

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/pUsSoGAyou

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Don't use your mask if it’s damaged or damp 💧

Disposable face coverings should also be thrown away after each use, or as soon as they become damp according to the World Health Organization 

Reusable face coverings need washed after every use

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/kVIbjdXAc4

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Do not share your mask

Sharing the mask with others could spread the virus - the mask has come into close contact with both of you

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/C6lmZBZdz0

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Don't touch the front of the mask 🦠

Be careful taking the mask off - clean your hands before and after
Wash your mask (if it's reusable), or dispose of it, after every use to avoid spreading the virus

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/DRTqyw6jwq

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Do not pull the mask away from your face to speak 🗣️

Coronavirus is spread when droplets are sprayed into the air when people cough, sneeze or talk, those droplets can then fall on surfaces

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/JO6mbfiZyY

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Don't wear loose fitting masks 

The mask should go from the top of your nose to under your mouth, with no gaps between your face and the material

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/2Bq2KWk3P9

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Do not wear your mask around the chin 😷

The mask should cover your mouth and nose and hook behind your face

If it's around your chin - it's not protecting anyone

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/JIzHDtRA5e

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The sugar tax was introduced in 2018

It was declared a success before it launched, as companies changed recipes

But tax paid each quarter since the introduction has been higher than the first, suggesting reduced sugary drink sales haven’t continued

 http://bbc.in/32XPj9o  pic.twitter.com/wcznEcnCRt

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Over the past decade, the gap in childhood obesity levels between the poorest and wealthiest increased from 8.5 percentage points to 13.5 percentage points

Obesity rates vary considerably across England

 http://bbc.in/32XPj9o  pic.twitter.com/ScLhR7SVIz

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
In 2008, measuring all primary school-aged children was introduced

In 2011, the coalition government targeted a sustained decrease in childhood obesity by 2020 

There's no data for 2020 yet, but there doesn't seem to have been a long-term decrease

 http://bbc.in/32XPj9o  pic.twitter.com/4j0TSdMXA4

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
In 2003, the government launched the 5-a-day campaign 

Since then, the proportion of adults eating five portions of fruit or veg increased from about 24% to about 28%

But, the proportion eating fewer than two portions a day stayed roughly the same - 27%

 http://bbc.in/32XPj9o  pic.twitter.com/H8geth6vSh

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Prime Minister Boris Johnson has announced a new obesity policy for England

There have been 12+ policies and white papers attempting to tackle obesity since 1997

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
How often should I wash my mask?

🧼 Wash after every use
🚰 Fabric coverings can be washed in your normal laundry
🔥 For other masks use hot water & scrub for 20+ seconds
☀️ Tumble dry on a high heat / air dry in direct sunlight
✨ Store in a clean place

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/klCd5Ulgi5

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
How should I make a face covering?

🧶 The more layers of material the better
😷 The mask needs to fit snugly around the face
👍 Tightly-woven cotton or twill, natural silk or quilted cotton work best 

You can make one with what you have at home: http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMakeAMask …

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Can I recycle my mask? 

🙅‍♂️ No 
🗑️ If your mask isn’t reusable or washable, place it in a bin to dispose of it
💧 Disposable face coverings should be thrown away after each use or if they become damp

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/4UIsTnsf3R

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
If you have breathing difficulties you're exempt from wearing face coverings, but if you want to wear one:

🤔 Try different types to see if one suits you 
🏡 Try one out at home, or on a short walk as a test
⚕️ Check with your doctor that it's safe

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/dth6mEtBDW

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
How do I stop a mask fogging up my glasses? 

🤓 Check for gaps where air escapes around your nose & cheeks
🤓 Tuck the mask behind your glasses or put tissue inside the top 
🤓 Rest your glasses on top of your mask

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/RardbL64iE

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Can I take my mask off to talk?

⛔ No 
🗣️ Coronavirus spreads when droplets are sprayed into the air when people cough, sneeze or talk
🦠 Those droplets can then fall on surfaces, so keep that mask on 

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/oqeygxNIS5

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
What mask should you buy? 

👩‍⚕️ Save surgical masks and respirators for key workers
🧣 Reusable cloth coverings, scarves and bandanas are fine
⚕️ Single-use coverings are available from most High Street stores
💅 Designer masks can now be purchased too

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/6pANqNO54O

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
How do you put a mask on properly? 

🧼 Clean your hands, before & after
👄 Cover your mouth & nose
👃 Make sure it goes to the top of you nose & hooks behind your face
😷 Check it’s snug - there shouldn't be gaps between the material and your face 

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/uX6mGs91jH

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
In England children aged 11+ will have to wear masks in shops from 24 July
In Scotland children aged 5+ must cover their faces in shops

On public transport across the UK, most passengers must wear masks

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMasks … pic.twitter.com/fWnPmR0V0t

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
How often should I wash my mask?

🧼 Wash after every use
🚰 Fabric coverings can be washed in your normal laundry
🔥 For other masks use hot water & scrub for 20+ seconds
☀️ Tumble dry on a high heat / air dry in direct sunlight
✨ Store in a clean place

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/BCryC84LlN

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
How should I make a face covering?

🧶 The more layers of material the better
😷 The mask needs to fit snugly around the face
👍 Tightly-woven cotton or twill, natural silk or quilted cotton works best 

You can make one with what you have at home: http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMakeAMask …

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Can I recycle my mask? 

🙅‍♂️ No 
🗑️ If your mask isn’t reusable, or washable place it in a bin to dispose of it
💧 Disposable face coverings should be thrown away after each use or if they become damp

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/6THWZnsH9R

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
If you have breathing difficulties you're exempt from wearing face coverings, but if you want to wear one:

🤔 Try different types to see if one suits you 
🏡 Try one out at home, or on a short walk as a test
⚕️ Check with your doctor, that it's safe http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide …

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
😷 How do I stop it fogging up my glasses? 

🤓 Check for gaps where air escapes around your nose & cheeks
🤓 Tuck the mask behind your glasses or put tissue inside the top 
🤓 Rest your glasses on top of your mask

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/rRXzua8Eol

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
😷 Can I take it off to talk?

⛔ No 
🗣️ Coronavirus is spread when droplets are sprayed into the air when people cough, sneeze or talk
🦠 Those droplets can then fall on surfaces, so keep that mask on 

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/gpOtGcB8Y7

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
😷 What mask should you buy? 

👩‍⚕️ Save surgical masks & respirators for key workers
🧣 Reusable cloth coverings, scarfs or bandanas will do
⚕️ Single-use coverings are available from most high street stores
💅 Designer masks can now be purchased too

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/eay6lxD0yx

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
😷 How do you put a mask on properly? 

🧼 Clean your hands, before & after
👄 Cover your mouth & nose
👃 Make sure it goes to the top of you nose & hooks behind your face
😷 Check it’s snug - there shouldn't be gaps between the material and your face 

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide … pic.twitter.com/bz2S8BqehV

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Masks are increasingly becoming a part of everyday life in the UK

But, we're not particularly used to wearing them

So, what do you need to know about putting on a mask? 😷

[Thread] http://bbc.in/CoronavirusMaskGuide …

tweet:
Health Secretary Matt Hancock says planning is under way for the expected surge in demand this winter

 http://bbc.in/CV19WinterUK  pic.twitter.com/UjrewhubbL

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:

 http://bbc.in/CV19WinterUK  pic.twitter.com/xZCsrM0DKy

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:

 http://bbc.in/CV19WinterUK  pic.twitter.com/34cH3Obm1u

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:

 http://bbc.in/CV19WinterUK  pic.twitter.com/9LWmjUPmeT

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
There is still a high degree of uncertainty over how the coronavirus pandemic will play out this winter

 http://bbc.in/CV19WinterUK  pic.twitter.com/wx6r0NPk5Q

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet: To find out more about how the government borrows money: http://bbc.in/CoronavirusBorrowingMoney …

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
What is the difference between government deficit and debt?

Debt is the total amount of money owed by the government that has built up over years

Debt rises when there is a deficit, and falls in those years when a government spends less than its income

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusBorrowingMoney … pic.twitter.com/bDhRmekR3Z

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
When does it have to be paid back?

It varies

Some government borrowing has to be repaid in a month, but some lending is for as long as 30 years

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusBorrowingMoney … pic.twitter.com/KGefoOjLb7

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
How does the government borrow money?

The government borrows in the financial markets by selling bonds - which is basically an interest-paying "IOU"

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusBorrowingMoney … pic.twitter.com/30G755OYDA

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The amount the government borrows to make up the difference between what it spends and what it collects is known as "public sector net borrowing" or "the deficit" 

New figures show borrowing in May was nine times higher than in the same month last year

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusBorrowingMoney … pic.twitter.com/3A0gNDU9Uw

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
So why does the government borrow money?

The government borrows because it spends more than it receives in revenue, which comes mainly from taxes

Currently government income is down because people are earning and spending less

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusBorrowingMoney … pic.twitter.com/MrLH357xrz

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The government has taken wide-ranging steps to try to limit the economic impact of coronavirus

But furlough schemes aren't cheap, and with government income also down, it may have to borrow more money than expected

[Thread]

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusBorrowingMoney …

tweet:
🇬🇧 Millions have accessed the furlough scheme

About 185,000 firms applied for the scheme on 20 April 

Since then 2/3 of businesses polled by the ONS reported they have furloughed at least part of their workforce

 http://bbc.in/CV19UK8  pic.twitter.com/x7KtOEjAz1

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
🇬🇧 Most children are still at home

There are now about 1.5 million children in England going to school, just over 15% of those registered

Schools in Wales have reopened, Scotland & NI will reopen schools in August, England's will reopen in September

 http://bbc.in/CV19UK8  pic.twitter.com/IrLOCEP4OB

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
🇬🇧 Doctors had more phone than face-to-face appointments

Only 14% of doctor's appointments were carried out over phone or video link in the year to February 2020

By May, more than half of appointments were carried out electronically ☎️
 http://bbc.in/CV19UK8  pic.twitter.com/lL9DHLFrOY

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
🇬🇧 Less A&E visits

The number of people attending Accident & Emergency fell below one million, while the numbers of calls made to the NHS hotline, 111, reached record highs

Experts say it's vital people continue to seek medical help if they need it

 http://bbc.in/CV19UK8  pic.twitter.com/AYOWZc2FAJ

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
🇬🇧 The UK is 'past the peak' of the disease

Looking at hospital deaths there is strong evidence the UK hit the peak on 8 April

The number of deaths in a single week has fallen below the 5 year average for the first time since mid-March, according to ONS

 http://bbc.in/CV19UK8  pic.twitter.com/D6299YVviP

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
🇬🇧 Visits to parks and beaches are up

Mobile phone data from the week after lockdown started shows vehicle use fell to a third of its pre-pandemic level

But, that rose after the first relaxation, peaking during the late May bank holiday weekend

 http://bbc.in/CV19UK8  pic.twitter.com/VHJvtfwOJc

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
🇬🇧 Lots of people think 'normal life' is a long way off

In the early days 1 in 10 people thought it would take more than a year for life to return to normal or that life would never return to normal

By June it was 1 in 4

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Leicester will remain in its current stage of lockdown until 18 July, at the earliest

Read the full timeline: http://bbc.in/CV19LeicesterTimeline …

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
By 1 July, government & local authorities agree on how to share data more smoothly

Leicester's mayor Sir Peter Soulsby says he hopes “other councils will be able to analyse what's happening in their area & avoid the necessity of a city-wide intervention”

 http://bbc.in/CV19LeicesterTimeline … pic.twitter.com/bLQ1GU1DFq

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The next day, 29 June, the government went for a strict lockdown 

At 2100 BST, the extended lockdown for the city was announced by Matt Hancock

He told Parliament that Leicester was seeing 135 cases for every 100,000 people, much higher than elsewhere

 http://bbc.in/CV19LeicesterTimeline … pic.twitter.com/7mafiaSmpG

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
On 28 June the government said they were considering options to deal with the outbreak 

MP Jonathan Ashworth said there was “no suggestion” of a lockdown

Leicester's mayor said it was “not helpful... to suggest there needs to be a city-wide lockdown”

 http://bbc.in/CV19LeicesterTimeline … pic.twitter.com/6fO1gAbSs0

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
At this point, both national and local governments knew there was an outbreak and had the data to see the extent

Westminster boosted testing capacity, while Leicester mapped exactly where the outbreak was 

No immediate lockdown was announced

 http://bbc.in/CV19LeicesterTimeline … pic.twitter.com/uyr13zLGdP

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
On 25 June, Leicester received data which gave them the postcodes of people who had tested positive

The government says they began offering this on 22 June, but councils had to sign a data security agreement first

 http://bbc.in/CV19LeicesterTimeline … pic.twitter.com/NpabvjsVWt

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The next day, 19 June, the government gave Leicester more information, including a NHS “digital dashboard” that included numbers of local tests and positive cases

Some areas got this from 11 June, but it was made available to Leicester eight days later

 http://bbc.in/CV19LeicesterTimeline … pic.twitter.com/BnH5xfvqfm

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
It was on 18 June that this information went public

Health Secretary Matt Hancock said “there is an outbreak right now in parts of Leicester that we're working hard to track down”, during the government press conference

 http://bbc.in/CV19LeicesterTimeline … pic.twitter.com/AmxNKirozs

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
On 17 June, Browne heard from the national Test and Trace team, who had also spotted an issue

They added some “really helpful” data

 http://bbc.in/CV19LeicesterTimeline … pic.twitter.com/0QEJdWe1kX

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The 15 June was the first time Browne “had any data that indicated we might need to do something”

This was when Public Health England (PHE) provided a feedback report, which he says confirmed that they also thought there was a genuine increase in cases

 http://bbc.in/CV19LeicesterTimeline … pic.twitter.com/wZBpdeqxXz

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
On 8 June, a school in the city closed after positive coronavirus tests

Boris Johnson has said this is when “the government first took notice, and acted on, what was going on in Leicester”

 http://bbc.in/CV19LeicesterTimeline … pic.twitter.com/2NKgF1lVrg

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The first signs of a problem were spotted in early June by the city’s director of public health, Ivan Browne

He saw that the number of people testing positive, but not in hospital, was rising daily 

 http://bbc.in/CV19LeicesterTimeline … pic.twitter.com/Ua0nJE2Uov

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Lockdown restrictions across England were eased this weekend, apart from in one city: Leicester

A coronavirus outbreak in the city means it will remain largely closed until at least 18 July

So, what led to this local lockdown?

[Thread] http://bbc.in/CV19LeicesterTimeline …

tweet:

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The British government has pledged to stop sending waste to non-OECD countries, meaning it can’t be exported to the developing world

But Turkey is in the OECD

So exports have soared

It now takes more of the UK's plastic waste than any other country

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:

Malaysia returned 42 shipping containers of unwanted waste to the UK earlier this year

tweet:

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet: Discover more top tips, and get the latest on the hot temperatures hitting the UK: https://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Tip 10: Remember, you will recover

We ideally need between seven to eight hours of quality sleep to function at our best, but a few nights of interrupted sleep will do no long-lasting damage

 https://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/4g8ka28j8M

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Tip 9: Keep an eye on your children

Children are normally quite sound sleepers once they nod off, but changes to routine can unsettle, so keep bed and bath times the same

Babies will sleep best when the temperature is kept between 16C and 20C

 https://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/3m3wKLmVEJ

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Tip 8: Stay calm

Keep yourself busy - worrying about how much sleep you might get before heading to bed doesn't help

And if you do struggle when in bed, read a book or listen to the radio, but avoid screen time 

 https://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/x6JiX3zRdF

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Trip 7: Think about what you drink

Soft drinks can contain stimulants such as caffeine that keep us awake

And, while it may feel the perfect time for a socially-distanced alcoholic drink, remember these can cause poor sleep and force us to wake earlier 

 https://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/xG3WGDbWRf

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Tip 6: Stay hydrated

Drink plenty of water throughout the day, but avoid too much right before you head to bed, as a trip to the bathroom in the early hours won't help your attempt at catching a good night's sleep

 https://bbc.in/HotSleepingTips  pic.twitter.com/atorSRjSOx

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Tip 5: Chill your socks

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
On 18 June the UK ditched its current version of the app completely, shifting to a model based on technology from Apple & Google

The Apple-Google design is promoted as being more privacy-focused, but it means epidemiologists will have access to less data

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKApp  pic.twitter.com/9ZUwP71WVl

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
On 5 June Business Minister Nadhim Zahawi expressed hope that the app would be running by the end of the month

But on 17 June Health Minister Lord Bethell told MPs the app was no longer a priority http://bbc.in/2V7i12V

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
On the 27 May the contact-tracing system was launched, without the nationwide app

According to government figures, in the first week tracers contacted 5,407 people with the virus

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKApp  pic.twitter.com/81PxgXPdJ4

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
On 20 May, PM Boris Johnson said the app would be “world-beating” and would be in place by 1 June

He also said announced 25,000 trackers who would "be able to cope with 10,000 new cases a day"

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKApp  pic.twitter.com/alEaf87zAf

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
On 5 May the app launched on the Isle of Wight

It was downloaded by under half the population there - ministers said it would need to be downloaded by 60%+

The trial aimed to see if the app was effective - if it was, it would be rolled out across the UK

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKApp  pic.twitter.com/N4dCD5jV2s

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
At the time, Google and Apple were trialling a different app - but the government preferred to go its own way

Now the NHS is set to work with these companies to work up a new design

So how did the app work in its trial phase?

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKApp  pic.twitter.com/PuShXVegg8

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Let’s rewind to 12 April when the app was launched

Health Secretary Matt Hancock announced the development of "a new NHS app for contact tracing"

The app would automatically alert users if they had been in contact with another user with coronavirus

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKApp  pic.twitter.com/tCIB5sNVwV

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
However it has emerged Apple did not know the UK was working on a "hybrid" version with Google

Apple said it was "difficult to understand" the claims

So when can we expect to see an app up and running? http://bbc.in/3dg9CQM

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
After months of work, the app which has been developed so far is being scrapped

A new approach will be tried based on a system created by Apple and Google

 http://bbc.in/CV19UKApp  pic.twitter.com/Q0dJ9ArHWw

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The UK’s coronavirus contact tracing app was due to be launched mid-May - to help control cases of Covid-19 within the country

But, it's still not available 

So, where is it, and what's happened?

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
What are excess deaths?

@BBCRealityCheck explains why statisticians say they can give us a better indication of how many people have actually died pic.twitter.com/JosOuCWXv3

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
London has been worst affected during the pandemic 

It has registered the highest number of excess deaths
 
But, the whole of the UK has felt the impact of coronavirus 

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusExcessDeaths … pic.twitter.com/3UDUDcaHpV

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Looking at the total number of excess deaths gives us a better understanding of the impact of the coronavirus pandemic on the country as a whole

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusExcessDeaths … pic.twitter.com/atVBrxaZJu

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Any additional excess deaths may have been, directly or indirectly, caused by the coronavirus pandemic

In the UK there have been 12,729 people in this category whose deaths are not officially attributed to Covid-19

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusExcessDeaths … pic.twitter.com/yJriNMW4mw

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Many of these excess deaths are people who count towards the coronavirus death toll

In the UK, 51,804 people had Covid-19 mentioned on their death certificates between 7 March and 5 June

But this does not account for all excess deaths

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusExcessDeaths … pic.twitter.com/YivLSsVsTW

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Any deaths above those expected deaths are known as “excess deaths”

Many countries around the world have recorded high numbers of excess deaths, since the pandemic began

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusExcessDeaths … pic.twitter.com/28ubNhx6HU

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
If 2020 had been an average year in the UK, the dotted line shows how many people we would have expected to die each week
 
This is known as expected deaths (it's calculated based on deaths in previous years)

 http://bbc.in/CoronavirusExcessDeaths … pic.twitter.com/dcojTSZddM

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The number of deaths in the UK during the coronavirus pandemic has been 43% above average, with about 64,500 more people dying than usual

Not all of those excess deaths will be from Covid-19, but the data gives an idea of the impact of the virus

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The WHO has welcomed the trial results, saying more therapies are now needed for milder symptoms

The findings are particularly good news for developing countries. In many African nations the drug costs less than two dollars

Follow the link to read more http://bbc.in/CV19WhatIsDexamethasone …

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Are there any side-effects?

Common side-effects when used for non-Covid conditions include anxiety, difficulty sleeping, weight gain and fluid retention

But coronavirus patients only need a relatively low dose which should limit side-effects

 http://bbc.in/CV19WhatIsDexamethasone … pic.twitter.com/y5FEzC1mDw

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
How widely available is the drug?

Dexamethasone is a low-cost drug which is in good supply

The UK government says it has stockpiled enough to treat 200,000 people

It costs from £5.40 a day per patient, in the UK

It's cheaper in developing countries

 http://bbc.in/CV19WhatIsDexamethasone … pic.twitter.com/ysz1TozbkS

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
What was the trial?

The results come from a University of Oxford trial that is testing whether existing medicines used for other conditions could be useful in treating Covid-19

 http://bbc.in/CV19WhatIsDexamethasone … pic.twitter.com/Tad72yzcZZ

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
How effective is it?

One in three deaths could be prevented among patients on ventilators, a UK trial showed

For patients on oxygen, it could prevent one death in five

 http://bbc.in/CV19WhatIsDexamethasone … pic.twitter.com/JFw8S0KHeY

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
How does it work?

Coronavirus infection triggers inflammation as the body tries to fight it off

But sometimes the immune system goes into overdrive and it's this reaction that can prove fatal

Dexamethasone calms this effect

 http://bbc.in/CV19WhatIsDexamethasone … pic.twitter.com/ySjB7dg845

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Dexamethasone is a steroid - a medicine that reduces inflammation by mimicking anti-inflammatory hormones produced by the body

 http://bbc.in/CV19WhatIsDexamethasone … pic.twitter.com/aUGrTTVvZF

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Dexamethasone has been hailed as a ground-breaking treatment for seriously ill coronavirus patients
What is the drug and how does it work?

[Thread] 👇
 http://bbc.in/CV19WhatIsDexamethasone …

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Dexamethasone doesn’t appear to help those with milder symptoms (those who don't need help with their breathing)

But, it is still a significant breakthrough - the first drug to “reduce mortality” from coronavirus http://bbc.in/CV19Dexamethasone …

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
As the drug is cheap and widely-available, it could be a huge benefit in poorer countries, struggling with Covid-19

“The treatment is up to 10 days of dexamethasone and it costs about £5 per patient,” says Prof Landray

 http://bbc.in/CV19Dexamethasone … pic.twitter.com/39V71gQ2Ax

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Prof Martin Landray says the findings suggest that for every eight patients treated on ventilators, you could save one life

For patients treated with oxygen, in theory, you save one life for every 20-25 treated with the drug

 http://bbc.in/CV19Dexamethasone … pic.twitter.com/HqbZe8a9Sf

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
Dexamethasone appears to help stop some of the damage that can happen when the body's immune system goes into overdrive as it tries to fight off coronavirus

This is called a cytokine storm

 http://bbc.in/CV19Dexamethasone … pic.twitter.com/aI836wnkyi

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The findings come from the world’s-biggest trial of existing treatments for use on coronavirus patients

If the drug had been used to treat UK patients from the start of the pandemic, up to 5,000 lives could have been saved, researchers estimate

 http://bbc.in/CV19Dexamethasone … pic.twitter.com/OPEcFtmMKw

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
The steroid, which is already used to treat some illnesses, was part of a trial run by Oxford University 

For Covid-19 patients on ventilators, risk of death was cut from 40% to 28%

For patients needing oxygen, it cut the risk of death from 25% to 20%

 http://bbc.in/CV19Dexamethasone … pic.twitter.com/zTdqIpCsmM

name: BBC News (UK)
tweet:
“A major breakthrough”

Scientists have found a cheap and widely-available drug which can help save lives of seriously ill coronavirus patients

It’s called Dexamethasone
